Company Li Description: Resources for your non-academic job search, curated by Ashley Ruba, PhD.
Lead Summary: For over a decade, I worked to become a professor at a top-tier research university. Then, I quit. Today, I'm a Human Factors Engineer helping other PhDs launch fulfilling non-academic careers.  The long version:  By every metric, my research program on early childhood emotional development was highly successful. In 2019, after I completed my PhD in Developmental Psychology, I received a prestigious post-doctoral fellowship from the National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH).   I also won two dissertation awards: the 2020 Dissertation Award in the Social Sciences from the University of Washington and the 2021 Dissertation Award in Developmental Psychology from the American Psychological Association (APA). I published fifteen first-author papers, which have been cited over 500 times.  But at a certain point, none of that mattered to me anymore. I had just turned 30, and I was a third-year post-doc with no academic job prospects. I was staring down a fourth (and potentially fifth) year as an underpaid and under-appreciated post-doc without career security.  I had no guarantee that I would land a faculty position in a place that I wanted to live, or felt safe living as a queer person. And, as a neurodivergent person who manages a stress-related disorder, my mental health was becoming worse and worse. How much more was I willing to give for this career?   I decided to quit. On January 24, 2022, I posted on Twitter that I was leaving academia. The tweet went viral. I continued to write about my career transition, offering free career advice and verbalizing the emotions that many academics shared but were afraid to express.  Today, I'm a Human Factors Engineer at Arthrex, developing digital technology to assist orthopedic surgeons. I earn more, work less, and feel so much happier compared to my academic career. And I‚Äôm on a mission to help other PhDs follow in my footsteps.  Why? Because I remember how lost and alone I felt during my career transition - I never want anyone else to feel this way. With resources and support, you too can launch a fulfilling non-academic career. You don't need to struggle like I did. Because you have value as a PhD.  You just need a strategy.   üíõ  P.S. - visit www.ashleyruba.com to learn my step-by-step strategy :)

Company Li Description: Synergy Medical Collective (SMC) is founded on the belief that healthcare companies are best built and run by people who have experience serving patients at the bedside.  SMC is different in that we promote teamwork and collaboration between all staff, every day, at all times. The aspirational goal of Synergy Medical Collective (SMC) is to provide a full end-to-end staffing solution for Emergency Departments.  Too often in Emergency Departments, doctors, nurses, techs, and support staff work in silos, only concerned with their specific tasks. This is highly inefficient and counterproductive to patient care. SMC is different in that we promote teamwork and collaboration between all staff, every day, at all times. This manner of work has been codified into the operational design of our company.  By providing partial or full staffing solutions for Emergency Departments, we create manageable workloads and prevent staff burnout. We can outperform other companies because our operating model understands the importance of EACH TEAM member, and we guarantee having the staffing resources needed to provide safe, comprehensive medical care, 7-days a week, 365-days per year.
Lead Summary: My name is Dr. Vincent Roddy and I am the founder of Synergy Medical Collective (SMC), a healthcare staffing firm based in Miami, Florida. I grew up in Northern Virginia and later attended Duke University where I earned my Bachelor's degree in Economics. I was also an active member of Kappa Alpha Psi, Fraternity incorporated, while serving as an economics teacher's assistant while at Duke.  Following college, I attended Virginia Commonwealth University's School of Medicine in Richmond, Virginia where I served as class president and earned my medical degree.  After completing my medical education, I pursued residency training in Emergency Medicine at Mount Sinai Hospital in New York City, a top-ranked hospital and research institution affiliated with the Icahn School of Medicine. During my time there, I honed my clinical skills and developed a passion for improving patient care through innovative solutions.  Following my residency, I moved to South Florida where I worked as an Emergency Physician and Assistant Medical Director at Broward Health Medical Center in Fort Lauderdale, later serving as Facility Medical Director at North Shore Medical Center in Miami, Florida. During this time, I saw firsthand the challenges that healthcare organizations faced in terms of staffing and productivity. I also saw how these challenges negatively impacted patient care.  Driven by a desire to improve healthcare staffing and productivity, I enrolled in business school while leading a team of physicians during the coronavirus pandemic. In 2022, I graduated from Duke University's Fuqua School of Business, where I was voted to be the student graduation speaker by my classmates, and earned my MBA degree. This experience gave me a unique perspective on the intersection of healthcare and business, and inspired me to start my own staffing firm.  In November 2022, I left my job as a medical director to start SMC, bringing SMC reforms and productivity-based compensation models to client hospitals. Our innovative approach is what is needed to save healthcare in the post-pandemic medical environment, and I am committed to improving patient care through our work!  In my free time, I enjoy reading, cooking, traveling, and spending time with family and friends. As a "Double Dukie," having earned two degrees from Duke University, I am also a passionate fan of Duke basketball.  If you are interested in business or media collaborations, please reach out.

Lead Summary: I was born and raised in New York City, but getting into the wilderness or finding patches of nature where one might least expect it is what drives me. Preserving wild places and wild things is what led me to energy and environmental entrepreneurship. A few creative ideas and a good amount of luck has helped get me into the executive suite in the clean energy transition + artificial intelligence + big data space. Playing the blues, a game of pickup ice hockey, or swimming in cold water in winter are also outdoor joys that keep me grounded.     In the future, I believe that energy will be clean, resilient, abundant, and free. Harnessing that energy will allow us to preserve wild places and protect the magic of our natural world, while propelling us to the far reaches of our solar system and beyond. We all have a role to play in the giant leaps that ai and energy abundance will produce for humanity, but if you ever need convincing that there is enough magic on earth to keep us busy with preservation and exploration, look up "giant clam" and see the incredible electric colors of an ocean behemoth. Consider that in 2008, 125,000+ lowland gorillas were discovered in a swamp in the DRC. Look at an Eastern Hellbender salamander here on the East Coast, whose rivers in West Virginia are vulnerable to coal production runoff.   We have a generational responsibility to leave this world better than we found it. At no time in human history has that goal, with all the tools, resources, ingenuity, and inspiration available to us, been more attainable. Who knows - your consciousness may live on forever, and the mind is as infinitely complex as the natural world, and only just being mapped and explored. Let's roll up our sleeves and get to work!

Company Li Description: NeuEve performs R&D, manufacturing and marketing for all-natural therapeutic remedies.
Lead Summary: People are often surprised when they meet me and learn that I co-founded NeuEve. People are confused, because things don't quite add up from their first impressions about me.   Some perceive me as a spoiled child who has never known hardship. Some perceive me as just a man, with nothing to contribute to solving women's issues. Some perceive me as just another cookie-cutter Asian nerdy tech guy. Others see me as "too nice" and therefore weak.  These first impressions couldn't be further from the truth.  The truth is that my life's struggles made me who I am, and I have made NeuEve the way it is.  As a child, I was shaped by two complete opposite goals and struggles. 1. I wanted to be extraordinary and change the world. 2. Deep down, all I really wanted was to be normal and accepted.  Let me you a paint a picture.  A shy, sensitive, bright Asian kid growing up fast like a beanstalk, in a middle class town in Kansas. The only Asian family for miles and miles around. I was blessed and cursed with a gift. The gift of being extremely smart.  I wanted to be liked, I wanted to have friends, I wanted my crush to like me back.  My mom, Dr. Renjie Chang, also desperately wanted me to be liked (as she was once very popular, back in China). Her advice to me was that people like you more when you get better grades.  So I did my duty. I completely demolished every single quiz and test. 100's all across the board.  The better I did in school, the more the other kids disliked me. "Teacher's Pet!" "Smart Aleck!" I felt more isolated and less accepted.  My childhood was like being a fly stuck in a spider web. I had a goal: to be liked and accepted. And the harder I tried, the farther from that goal I got.  I remember feeling angry and confused often. The more others attacked me, the more hardened I felt in my identity.  ‚Äî  At age 12, I remember watching Pay It Forward for the first time. This movie inspired me and it gave me a hope and a vision for a way out of my dilemma.  In the movie, this optimistic boy decides to invent an idea to change the world. It's simple: do 3 big things for 3 people. And after you do these big things, ask them to do 3 big things for 3 other people! It's basically a pyramid scheme or chain-letter of kindness. In the movie, the boy successfully changes the world and becomes a timeless hero.  I started believing that, maybe if I could change the world, people would finally like me and accept me.  ‚Äî  Continued at >> https://www.neueve.com/pages/kevin-tao
